<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="370" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,320,599]" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,308,393,419]" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Remarks</emphasis>
. The male can be separable from the other members of this genus by the AR more than 2.5 and the distinct circular patches of setal tuft on T I–III. The pupa is distinct in the large plastron plate, the robust, pigmented Dc 
<subScript attach="left" box="[184,192,483,497]" fontSize="6" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">1</subScript>
, and the posterolateral corner of T III–V without pedes spurii A. In the original description (
<bibRefCitation author="Paul, N. &amp; Hazra, N. &amp; Mazumdar, A." box="[1234,1424,464,491]" pageId="5" pageNumber="370" pagination="498 - 504" refId="ref13945" refString="Paul, N., Hazra, N. &amp; Mazumdar, A. (2013) Records of the genus Paramerina (Diptera: Chironomidae: Tanypodinae) from Eastern Himalaya and Satpura Hill Regions of India. Neotropical Entomology, 42 (5), 498 - 504. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / s 13744 - 013 - 0149 - x" type="journal article" year="2013">
Paul 
<emphasis box="[1293,1350,464,490]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">et al.</emphasis>
, 2013
</bibRefCitation>
), the authors wrote, “Tergite IX normal with posterior row of 7–9 setae.” We found the position and number of the circular patches are also wrong in the figure of the original description which we have corrected here (
<figureCitation box="[1261,1381,536,563]" captionStart="FIGURES 3" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1759,1783]" captionTargetBox="[278,1330,215,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-33@6.[244,1344,181,1735]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 3A–C. A. Abdomen of male Zavrelimyia (Paramerina) valida (Paul, Mazumdar and Hazra, 2013); B. Hypopygium of male Zavrelimyia (Paramerina) valida (Paul, Mazumdar and Hazra, 2013); C. Hypopygium of male Zavrelimyia (Schineriella) schineri (Strobl, 1880). Both to scale: 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6644854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6644854/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Figure 3A</figureCitation>
). We examined the 
<typeStatus box="[308,406,572,598]" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">holotype</typeStatus>
and 
<typeStatus box="[461,568,573,599]" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">paratypes</typeStatus>
and it was revealed that the T IX (
<figureCitation box="[955,1070,572,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 3" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1759,1783]" captionTargetBox="[278,1330,215,1685]" captionTargetId="figure-33@6.[244,1344,181,1735]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 3A–C. A. Abdomen of male Zavrelimyia (Paramerina) valida (Paul, Mazumdar and Hazra, 2013); B. Hypopygium of male Zavrelimyia (Paramerina) valida (Paul, Mazumdar and Hazra, 2013); C. Hypopygium of male Zavrelimyia (Schineriella) schineri (Strobl, 1880). Both to scale: 50 µm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6644854" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6644854/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="370">Figure 3B</figureCitation>
) has no transverse row setae.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
